7 An Act relating to professions and occupations;
amending 59 O.S. 2021, Sections 1003, 1005, and 1009,
8 which relate to definitions, examinations, and
duration of plumbing licenses; modifying, adding and
9 deleting definitions; updating statutory references;
requiring certain score on plumbing examination;
10 establishing certain qualifications for plumbing
examinations; establishing certain license time
11 period; providing for codification; and providing an
effective date.
12
13
14 AMENDMENT NO. 1. Page 1, strike the title, enacting clause and
entire bill and insert
15
16 “An Act relating to professions and occupations;
amending 59 O.S. 2021, Sections 1003, 1005, 1006, and
17 1009, which relate to The Plumbing License Law of
1955; modifying definitions; decreasing certain
18 prohibited examination period; establishing certain
passing score; allowing Construction Industries Board
19 to issue licenses to certain persons; requiring
certain plumbing contractors to meet certain
20 requirements; limiting certain residential plumbers
to certain buildings; updating statutory language;
21 and providing an effective date.
22 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
23 SECTION 1. AMENDATORY 59 O.S. 2021, Section 1003, is
24 amended to read as follows:
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 3462 Page 1

1 Section 1003. As used in The Plumbing License Law of 1955:
2 1. “Board” means the Construction Industries Board;
3 2. “Committee” means the Oklahoma State Committee of Plumbing
4 Examiners appointed by the Construction Industries Board;
5 3. “Plumbing Hearing Board” means the State Plumbing Hearing
6 Board which shall consist of a designee of the Construction
7 Industries Board, as chair, and the members of the Oklahoma State
8 Committee of Plumbing Examiners;
9 4. “Apprentice” or “plumber’s apprentice” means any person
10 sixteen (16) years of age or older who, as the principal occupation
11 of the person, is engaged in learning and assisting in the
12 installation of plumbing under the direct supervision of a licensed
13 journeyman plumber or plumbing contractor;
14 5. “Journeyman plumber” means any person other than a master
15 plumber or plumbing contractor who engages in or works at the actual
16 installation, alteration, repair, and/or or renovation of plumbing
17 site;
18 6. “Temporary journeyman plumber” means any person other than a
19 person permanently licensed as a journeyman plumber, master plumber,
20 or plumbing contractor in this state who meets the temporary
21 licensure requirements of Section 1006.1 of this title;
22 7. “Master plumber” is a term used and defined under laws which
23 have been repealed. A person formerly known as a master plumber is
24
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 3462 Page 2

1 henc eforth to be known as a “plumbing contractor” as defined in this
2 section;
3 8. “Plumbing contractor” means any person who is skilled in the
4 planning, superintending, and practical installation of plumbing and
5 who is familiar with the laws and rules governing the same. This
6 definition may be construed to mean any person who has qualified and
7 is licensed under The Plumbing License Law of 1955 as a plumbing
8 contractor, who may operate as an individual, a firm, partnership,
9 limited liability company, or corporation, or other legal entity to
10 engage in the business of plumbing, or the business of contracting
11 to do plumbing, or furnish labor or materials or both for the
12 installation, repair, maintenance, or renovation of plumbing
13 according to the requirements of The Plumbing License Law of 1955;
14 9. 8. “Plumbing” means, and includes:
15 a. all piping, fixtures, appurtenances, and appliances
16 for, and in connection with, a supply of water within
17 or adjacent to any building, structure, or conveyance,
18 on the premises and to the connection with a water
19 main or other source of supply,
20 b. all piping, fixtures, appurtenances, and appliances
21 for sanitary drainage or storm drainage facilities,
22 including venting systems for such facilities, within
23 or adjacent to any building, structure, or conveyance,
24
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 3462 Page 3

1 on the premises and to the connection with a public
2 disposal system or other acceptable terminal,
3 c. the installation, repair, maintenance, and renovation
4 of all piping, fixtures, appurtenances, and appliances
5 for a supply of water, or for the disposal of waste
6 water, liquid waste, or sewage within or adjacent to
7 any building, structure, or conveyance, on the
8 premises and to the source of supply of water or point
9 of disposal of wastes, and
10 d. the installation, repair, and maintenance of radiant-
11 floor heating system piping in residential homes with
12 capacities no greater than one hundred thousand
13 (100,000) BTU’s BTUs using only piping approved by the
14 most current adopted edition of the International
15 Mechanical Code; and
16 9. “Residential journeyman plumber” means any person who is
17 qualified and licensed, other than a plumbing contractor, to engage
18 in or work at the actual installation, alteration, repair, or
19 renovation site of residential plumbing. Residential plumbing shall
20 be limited to the type and category of journeyman plumbing license
21 for supervising and performing plumbing work for detached one- or
22 two-family dwellings and does not include commercial plumbers; and
23 10. “Variance and Appeals Board” means the Oklahoma State
24 Plumbing Installation Code Variance and Appeals Board.
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 3462 Page 4

1 SECTION 2. AMENDATORY 59 O.S. 2021, Section 1005, is
2 amended to read as follows:
3 Section 1005. (a) A. Examinations shall be uniform and shall
4 be practical in nature but sufficiently strict to test the
5 qualification and fitness of the applicant as a journeyman plumber
6 or residential journeyman plumber or as a plumbing contractor, as
7 the case may be. It shall be in whole or in part in writing.
8 (b) B. Regular examinations shall be held at least twice each
9 year and special examinations may be fixed by the Oklahoma State
10 Committee of Plumbing Examiners. Any applicant initially failing to
11 pass the examination shall not be permitted to take another
12 examination for a period of thirty (30) days, and thereafter any
13 such applicant subsequently failing to pass the examination shall
14 not be permitted to take a subsequent examination for a period of
15 ninety (90) days thirty (30) days.
16 C. A passing score on all examinations shall be a grade not
17 less than seventy percent (70%).
18 SECTION 3. AMENDATORY 59 O.S. 2021, Section 1006, is
19 amended to read as follows:
20 Section 1006. A. The Construction Industries Board shall issue
21 licenses to persons who have been certified by the Board as having
22 successfully passed the examination for journeyman plumber or,
23 plumbing contractor, or residential journeyman plumber, as the case
24
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 3462 Page 5

1 may be, and who have paid the fees and have otherwise complied with
2 the applicable requirements of The Plumbing License Law of 1955.
3 B. Plumbing contractors shall meet the same requirements as
4 applicants for the journeyman plumber examination with an additional
5 one (1) year of experience. Plumbing contractors shall notify their
6 surety of any municipalities wherein plumbing work will be performed
7 and may operate as an individual, firm, partnership, limited
8 liability company, or corporation, or other legal entity to engage
9 in the business of plumbing, or the business of contracting to do
10 plumbing.
11 C. Residential plumbers shall be limited to engage in work on
12 one- and two-family dwelling units in a singularly constructed
13 structure that have a maximum of two dwelling units for each
14 structure, and have a minimum of five (5) feet of separation of
15 construction to any other dwelling unit or structure regardless and
16 independent of firewalls, such as a single independent residential
17 home or duplex. Residential plumbers shall not engage in work on
18 dwelling units or structures that include occupancies of more than
19 two dwelling units such as apartments, motels, and multifamily
20 townhomes.
21 D. A residential journeyman plumber license shall entitle the
22 licensee to install plumbing as defined in OAC 158:30-1-2. To
23 engage in the act of residential plumbing, a residential journeyman
24 plumber shall be employed and supervised by a licensed plumbing
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 3462 Page 6

1 cont ractor. A residential journeyman plumber shall not contract or
2 furnish labor and materials. If a residential journeyman plumber
3 performs plumbing work in commercial industrial plumbing, he or she
4 shall be employed by a licensed plumbing contractor and maintain an
5 apprentice plumber registration, as defined in OAC 158:30-5-1.
6 E. Applicants for a journeyman plumber examination shall be
7 eighteen (18) years of age or older and have:
8 1. Three (3) years of experience in the plumbing trade while
9 employed by a licensed plumbing contractor; or
10 2. Three (3) years of experience in the plumbing trade while
11 serving in the United States Armed Forces.
12 F. Applicants for a residential journeyman plumber examination
13 shall be eighteen (18) years of age or older and have:
14 1. Two (2) years and four thousand (4,000) verified hours of
15 work experience in the plumbing trade while employed by a licensed
16 plumbing contractor;
17 2. An associate’s degree or vocational diploma certifying
18 completion of a formal plumbing education program approved by the
19 Oklahoma State Committee of Plumbing Examiners consisting of a
20 minimum of one thousand (1,000) classroom hours from an educational
21 institution approved by the Committee and three thousand (3,000)
22 verified hours of work experience in the plumbing trade while
23 employed by a licensed plumbing contractor; or
24
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 3462 Page 7

1 3. Two (2) years of experience in the plumbing trade while
2 serving in the United States Armed Forces and three thousand (3,000)
3 verified hours of work experience in the plumbing trade while
4 employed by a licensed plumbing contractor.
5 G. A verifiable out-of-state plumbing license may be used to
6 expedite processing of the requirements or be considered for
7 reciprocity pursuant to OAC 158:30-5-4 if there is a written
8 reciprocity agreement with that state, the license is currently in
9 good standing, and the licensee meets the requirements set forth in
10 subsections E and F of this section.
11 H. All licenses shall be nontransferable. It shall be unlawful
12 for any holder of a license under The Plumbing License Law of 1955
13 to loan or allow the use of such license by any other person, firm
14 or corporation, except as specifically provided in The Plumbing
15 License Law of 1955.
16 C. I. The Board shall adopt procedures and rules to review and
17 accept proof and documentation of an applicant’s qualified training
18 and experience as a journeyman plumber or, plumbing contractor, or
19 residential journeyman plumber while on active duty with the armed
20 forces Armed Forces of the United States when such service member
21 has been honorably discharged from active duty within one (1) year
22 of the application for examination or licensure in this state as a
23 journeyman plumber or, plumbing contractor, or residential
24 journeyman plumber.
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 3462 Page 8

1 SECTION 4. AMENDATORY 59 O.S. 2021, Section 1009, is
2 amended to read as follows:
3 Section 1009. A. No license shall be issued for longer than
4 one (1) year and all licenses shall expire on the last day in the
5 birth month of the licensee and shall be in alignment with
6 continuing education requirements. Such licenses may be renewed
7 upon application and payment of fees within thirty (30) days
8 preceding or following the date the license renewal is due. No
9 journeyman or contractor license shall be renewed unless the
10 licensee has completed the required hours of continuing education as
11 determined and approved by the Oklahoma State Committee of Plumbing
12 Examiners.
13 B. The Committee may renew licenses upon application made more
14 than thirty (30) days following the date of expiration only upon
15 payment of the renewal and additional fee prescribed and upon
16 compliance with any applicable continuing education requirements as
17 established by the Construction Industries Board and this act The
18 Plumbing License Law of 1955. Provided, that no penalty for renewal
19 shall be charged to any holder of a license which expires while such
20 holder is in military service if application is made within one (1)
21 year following discharge from the military service.
22 C. Apprentice registration certificates expire one (1) year
23 after date of registration, at which time the apprentice may
24 reregister.
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 3462 Page 9

1 SECTION 5. This act shall become effective November 1, 2026.”
